Discount -> PremiumUserDiscount/FestiveDiscount/NoDiscount



Problem Statement (Realistic)

Final price depends on:

User type (Regular / Premium)
Coupon applied
Festival offers

👉 We want to plug different discount strategies dynamically.

Common Interview Trap

👉 “Can we apply multiple discounts together?”

Answer:

❌ Strategy → Only ONE algorithm at a time
✅ If multiple needed → use Decorator Pattern
⚡ When to Use Strategy in E-commerce

Use it when:

Multiple interchangeable business rules exist
You want to avoid if-else chains
Logic may grow in future

If you want next level (very powerful for your experience):

👉 I can combine:

Strategy (discount selection)
Decorator (stack multiple discounts)
Spring Boot (real implementation)


=======================================




combine strategy and decorator design pattern

Good—this is exactly how real pricing engines are built.
Strategy decides which discount logic to use, and Decorator lets you stack multiple adjustments (coupon + tax + delivery + etc).

Let’s design a clean, production-style e-commerce pricing engine.

🛒 Problem Statement

Final price should support:

Strategy → choose base discount (Festival / Premium)
Decorator → add:
Coupon discount
Tax
Delivery charges

👉 Example:

Base Price → Festival Discount (Strategy)
→ Coupon → Tax → Delivery (Decorators)
✅ Design Overview
PricingStrategy → Strategy
PriceComponent → Base interface
BasePrice → Concrete component
PriceDecorator → Abstract decorator
Concrete decorators → Coupon, Tax, Delivery
🧩 Complete Code
1. Strategy Interface
interface PricingStrategy {
    int applyBaseDiscount(int amount);
}
2. Strategy Implementations
class NoDiscountStrategy implements PricingStrategy {
    public int applyBaseDiscount(int amount) {
        return amount;
    }
}

class FestivalStrategy implements PricingStrategy {
    public int applyBaseDiscount(int amount) {
        return amount - (amount * 10 / 100);
    }
}

class PremiumStrategy implements PricingStrategy {
    public int applyBaseDiscount(int amount) {
        return amount - 200;
    }
}
3. Component Interface
interface PriceComponent {
    int getPrice();
    String getDescription();
}
4. Base Component
class BasePrice implements PriceComponent {

    private int basePrice;
    private PricingStrategy strategy;

    public BasePrice(int basePrice, PricingStrategy strategy) {
        this.basePrice = basePrice;
        this.strategy = strategy;
    }

    @Override
    public int getPrice() {
        return strategy.applyBaseDiscount(basePrice);
    }

    @Override
    public String getDescription() {
        return "Base Price after Strategy";
    }
}
5. Abstract Decorator
abstract class PriceDecorator implements PriceComponent {
    protected PriceComponent component;

    public PriceDecorator(PriceComponent component) {
        this.component = component;
    }
}
6. Concrete Decorators
🎟️ Coupon
class CouponDecorator extends PriceDecorator {

    public CouponDecorator(PriceComponent component) {
        super(component);
    }

    @Override
    public int getPrice() {
        return component.getPrice() - 100;
    }

    @Override
    public String getDescription() {
        return component.getDescription() + " + Coupon";
    }
}
🧾 Tax (10%)
class TaxDecorator extends PriceDecorator {

    public TaxDecorator(PriceComponent component) {
        super(component);
    }

    @Override
    public int getPrice() {
        int price = component.getPrice();
        return price + (price * 10 / 100);
    }

    @Override
    public String getDescription() {
        return component.getDescription() + " + Tax";
    }
}
🚚 Delivery
class DeliveryDecorator extends PriceDecorator {

    public DeliveryDecorator(PriceComponent component) {
        super(component);
    }

    @Override
    public int getPrice() {
        return component.getPrice() + 50;
    }

    @Override
    public String getDescription() {
        return component.getDescription() + " + Delivery";
    }
}
7. Client Code
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {

        int baseAmount = 1000;

        // Step 1: Apply Strategy
        PricingStrategy strategy = new FestivalStrategy();
        PriceComponent price = new BasePrice(baseAmount, strategy);

        // Step 2: Apply Decorators dynamically
        price = new CouponDecorator(price);
        price = new TaxDecorator(price);
        price = new DeliveryDecorator(price);

        System.out.println(price.getDescription());
        System.out.println("Final Price: " + price.getPrice());
    }
}
🧠 Example Output
Base Price after Strategy + Coupon + Tax + Delivery
Final Price: 1045
🔥 Why This Design is Powerful
✅ Strategy handles:
“Which discount to apply?”
Cleanly replaceable logic
✅ Decorator handles:
“What all extra adjustments to add?”
Stackable features
⚡ Real E-commerce Mapping
Feature	Pattern
Festival / Premium discount	Strategy
Coupon stacking	Decorator
Tax calculation	Decorator
Delivery fee	Decorator
🚀 Senior-Level Insight (This is what impresses interviewers)

👉 In real systems:

Strategy is selected using Factory / DB config
Decorators are applied based on:
User input
Cart rules
Feature flags

👉 You might even build:

List<PriceDecorator> decorators

and apply in loop (dynamic pipeline)

⚠️ Important Interview Point

👉 Why combine both?

Answer:

Strategy is good for selecting one algorithm, but when multiple pricing rules need to be applied together, Decorator provides a flexible way to chain them without modifying existing code.